        <span title="prefix" class="quotePrefix">odies of knowledge) connect in e</span>
        <span title="quote" class="quoteExact">ndless circuits; these connections among bodies draw off pleasure. Social machines or assemblages organize “partial” investments (e.g., the infant’s pleasure at the mother’s breast) into larger assem- blages—organized institutions such as “motherhood” or “the family” (Colebrook, 2002, p. 82).</span>
        <span title="suffix" class="quoteSuffix">Much of the importance of the a</span>
      
        </div>
        <div class="annotationText">
          <p>Seeing connections to Blake here. This idea that everything is born of desire. I contrast this though with Kristeva's focus on the abject or aversion. As if meaning is antithetical to desire. Is one a more feminist interpretation of intertextuality where one class finds aversion in the desire of others? Where pain is a byproduct of someone else's desires?</p>
